04505nam a22005175i 9780228002659DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280026597 a10.1515/97802280026592doi  a(DE-B1597)657199  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR9185.2b.H88 2020 7aLIT0040802bisacsh04a809/.897132231 aHutchings, Kevin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTransatlantic Upper Canada :bPortraits in Literature Land and British-Indigenous Relations /cKevin Hutchings. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource :b8 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Transatlantic Studies ;v200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Literature, Land, and Colonial Relations -- tRomantic Ecology, Indigenous Culture, and the Ideology of “Improvement” -- tBishop John Strachan, Christian Evangelism, and the First Nations of Upper Canada -- tThe Legal, Literary, and Environmental Passions of Sir John Beverley Robinson -- tAnna Brownell Jameson and Sir Francis Bond Head among the Anishinaabeg -- tThe Transatlantic World of John Norton (Chief Teyoninhokarawen) -- tJohn Brant (Chief Ahyonwaeghs) and the Grand River Haudenosaunee -- tPeter Jones (Chief Kahkewaquonaby) and the Credit River Mississauga -- tThe Atlantic Crossings of George Copway (Kahgegagahbowh) -- tAfterword: Paths Not Taken -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLiterature emerging from nineteenth-century Upper Canada, born of dramatic cultural and political collisions, reveals much about the colony's history through its contrasting understandings of nature, ecology, deforestation, agricultural development, and land rights. In the first detailed study of literary interactions between Indigenous people and colonial authorities in Upper Canada and Britain, Kevin Hutchings analyzes the period's key figures and the central role that romanticism, ecology, and environment played in their writings. Investigating the ties that bound Upper Canada and Great Britain together during the early nineteenth century, Transatlantic Upper Canada demonstrates the existence of a cosmopolitan culture whose implications for the land and its people are still felt today. The book examines the writings of Haudenosaunee leaders John Norton and John Brant and Anishinabeg authors Jane Johnston Schoolcraft, Peter Jones, and George Copway, as well as European figures John Beverley Robinson, John Strachan, Anna Brownell Jameson, and Sir Francis Bond Head. Hutchings argues that, despite their cultural differences, many factors connected these writers, including shared literary interests, cross-Atlantic journeys, metropolitan experiences, mutual acquaintance, and engagement in ongoing dialogue over Indigenous territory and governance. A close examination of relationships between peoples and their understandings of land, Transatlantic Upper Canada creates a rich portrait of the nineteenth-century British Atlantic world and the cultural and environmental consequences of colonialism and resistance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCanadian literaturexIndian authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian literaturezOntarioy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEcology in literature. 0aEnvironmentalism in literature. 0aRomanticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228002659?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228002659423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228002659/original  aGBV-deGruyter-all